Chord containing a major third.  A major third is two whole tones above the tonic, or four semi-tones.  A major chord can have as few as two notes (tonic and major third), but harmonically the simplest major chord has three notes: the tonic, the major third, and the fifth.  For example, C, E and G respectively.  Chords can be inverted: the bass note does not have to be the tonic.